default3.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultNHS spending on diabetes was almost £10 billion in 2011, which was 10 per cent of the NHS budget. 80 per cent of NHS spending on diabetes goes into managing avoidable complications. People with diabetes account for around 19 per cent of hospital inpatients at any one time, and have a three day longer stay on average than people without diabetes. Most of type 2 diabetes c
defaultosts are due to hospitalisation.
default3
default3.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMore effective risk factor management in the community has the potential to reduce costs to the NHS
default, while 
defaultimproving quality of care
default.
default3.2.1.
default 
defaultEvidence into Practi
defaultce (
defaultEiP
default) is a
default clinical change manag
defaultement programme
default. The 
defaultprogramme
default 
defaultaims to ensure that people with diabetes and those at increased cardio-metabolic risk receive 
defaultoptimal care
default through the effective implementation of national policy and guidelines, particularly NICE Type 2 Diabetes Guidelines
default. 
defaultAn example of the success of this approach was demonstrated in Greenwich. R
defaultesults after one year show
defaulted
